    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3405201303" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3405201303" />
    <a title="Uhtred" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/109743598-uhtred"><img alt="Uhtred" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1581262401p2/109743598.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3405201303?book_show_action=true">Jun 22, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Uhtred" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Uhtred" href="/user/show/109743598-uhtred">Uhtred</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9788804370857" href="/book/show/820645.Il_barone_rampante">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3405201303" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12690375082285641131">I reread after many years &quot;The Baron in the trees&quot;, the second novel of the trilogy &quot;Our ancestors&quot;, after having just reread the first, &quot;The Cloven Viscount&quot;, and after this I will read the third, The Nonexistent Knight. I have a good memory of when I first read them as a teenager and I am curious to see how I will find them now, as an adult.<br/>The plot is set in the eighteenth century and is narrated in first person by Biagio, the protagonist&apos;s brother, that is Cosimo Piovasco di Rondò (without a</span>
  <span id="freeText12690375082285641131" style="display:none">I reread after many years "The Baron in the trees", the second novel of the trilogy "Our ancestors", after having just reread the first, "The Cloven Viscount", and after this I will read the third, The Nonexistent Knight. I have a good memory of when I first read them as a teenager and I am curious to see how I will find them now, as an adult.<br />The plot is set in the eighteenth century and is narrated in first person by Biagio, the protagonist's brother, that is Cosimo Piovasco di Rondò (without a name like what Baron would it be?). Cosimo is the son of a noble Ligurian family and when he is twelve years old, after a quarrel with his parents on a matter related to a plate of snails, he climbs on a tree in the home garden and never goes down again. Cosimo begins the thing like a whim, but then makes it a true lifestyle: being always in the trees he moves through woods and forests and gradually builds his complete existence on the trees. Cosimo meets Viola, a young girl he falls in love with, then finds a faithful friend in the dog Ottimo Massimo, and becomes very popular with the inhabitants of his lands. His is a path of growth in all senses: he knows the children of his country, becomes a friend of the outlaw Gian de Brughi, to whom he even teaches the beauty of reading, he studies philosophy, even becomes a pen pal of Voltaire, he organizes the inhabitants of his lands in groups against the fires in the woods, in short, he is very busy. The story with Viola, however, takes an unpleasant turn and due to a misunderstanding, the two move away and Viola will then marry another. Meanwhile, we have arrived at the time of the French Revolution and Cosimo also meets Napoleon, who however leaves him rather disappointed, as he had another idea of Napoleon. Cosimo's story ends with a beautiful twist in full Calvinian fairytale style: Cosimo, now grown old and tired, keeps his promise until the end and does not go ashore, but at the passage of a hot air balloon, he clings to a dangling rope and disappears on the horizon, leaving us as if we saw it disappear.<br />The story is very original: Cosimo's choice is not an escape from the world and from the people: his choice is the will of a man who wants to fully follow a promise he made to himself, as if without this promise you couldn't tell who Cosimo really is. It is a bit twisted but it is as if Cosimo thought that to live fully and be of real help to others the only way for him was to be separated from the others. It is true that Cosimo necessarily looks down on everyone, but he does it much less than certain misanthropes living on earth ...<br />As a teenager I had read it as a children's book, although they told me that it could be read on several levels, but in school age you can see above all the "light" part of the plot, which is however beautiful. As an adult I find these sensations again, but for sure with many other things: Calvino’s paradoxical characters and his improbable stories are not parodies, instead, they can be metaphors. Cosimo's choice seems far-fetched, but his constancy, his stubbornness, his coherence are the seal of those who believe in a cause to the end, so much so as to dedicate his whole life to it. You may not agree with them, but the consistency of certain people certainly impresses you. Cosimo does not accept compromises, he is faithful to himself and his promise, without regards to how uncomfortable it is. Cosimo climbs the tree on a whim as a child, but does not remain a child on the tree: over the branches his growth continues, solitary but not a voluntary hermit. He lives the passing of the seasons, reads many books, recognizes the sense of power when people called him Mister Baron, knows love and also sex, becomes an adult and then becomes old, with always that small distance from the earth (a jump would be enough ) which is like an impassable wall. We know Cosimo as a twelve year old and then we see him as an old man, hunchbacked and wrinkled, with his hairy coat, consistent up to the impossible. Impossible for us, not for Cosimo, and not for Calvino's ideal, who presents us with the refusal of compromise as the only way to defend the truest part of us, up to grab that hook in the middle of the sky and disappear on the horizon . Definitely 6 stars.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12690375082285641131" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


