    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2561414076" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2561414076" />
    <a title="Girish" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5924440-girish"><img alt="Girish" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1591866419p2/5924440.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2561414076?book_show_action=true">Oct 26, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Girish" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Girish" href="/user/show/5924440-girish">Girish</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2561414076" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18356949086639050933"><i>&quot;If I were not Napolean, I would want to be the citizen Cosimo Piovasco di Rondò&quot; </i> exclaims Napolean Bonaparte after meeting our Baron in the trees. <br/><br/>The extrordinary tale of Cosimo Piovasco di Rondò, the baron who in adoloscent rebellion, moves into the trees and never comes down is an exercise in metaphors. 12 year old Cosimo challenges the authority of his father to make him eat snails and goes up the tree. Everyone assumes he will come back, but with the stubborness of idea, Cosimo soon start</span>
  <span id="freeText18356949086639050933" style="display:none"><i>"If I were not Napolean, I would want to be the citizen Cosimo Piovasco di Rondò" </i> exclaims Napolean Bonaparte after meeting our Baron in the trees. <br /><br />The extrordinary tale of Cosimo Piovasco di Rondò, the baron who in adoloscent rebellion, moves into the trees and never comes down is an exercise in metaphors. 12 year old Cosimo challenges the authority of his father to make him eat snails and goes up the tree. Everyone assumes he will come back, but with the stubborness of idea, Cosimo soon starts adapting to his new truth and goes on to become a legend. <br /><br />Though the response seems exaggerated (and ridiculous), don't we consider any rebellion whose ideas seem new to be silly? From his new position, he learns to exercise his free will to help people - be it gathering people to prevent forest fires, stopping pirates, reading to a brigand before his execution and later becoming an military emissary. He goes on to establish the secret society of free masons of Italy <br /><br />Calvino keeps reminding us he is still the young boy who refused to have snail. He falls in love with Viola and get's his heart broken. He tends to his ailing mother without giving up on his principle. He suffers pangs of jealousy and loneliness. In effect, a rebel just in the eyes of the society, but every bit human.<br /><br /><i>"We'll make an army in the trees and bring the earth and the people on it to their senses"</i><br /><br />The metaphor for independence is understated. When he meets a spanish tribe banished to live in the trees, the tribal head exclaims awe at his choice vs resignation of his people. The world has very few individuals of today, who act dedicated to an idea than conform to the norm. He ends up doing much more for the people, the more distant in physical space he gets away from them. Like the futility of war.<br /><br />The book has some hilarious episodes like the brigand who falls in loves with books. It does slow down considerably after the 75% stage. The narrator, his younger brother, is impartial and candidly tells us there are many versions of each episode and he isn't sure which is the truth.(this alone, in an 1950s book is quite post modernist!) But an almost fable from this author who meditates on love and it's pain caught be off guard.<br /><br />An easier Calvino, but not his most profound.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18356949086639050933" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


