<div id="review_3182394129" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3182394129" />
    <a title="sologdin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5610133-sologdin"><img alt="sologdin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1307928658p2/5610133.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3182394129?book_show_action=true">Feb 08, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="sologdin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="sologdin" href="/user/show/5610133-sologdin">sologdin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5610133-sologdin?shelf=of-best-sentence-and-moost-solaas">of-best-sentence-and-moost-solaas</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3182394129" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3530622690658731661">Calvino reports, in one of the <i>Hermit in Paris</i> essays, that he wrote this novel in response to leaving the communist party, after the 1956 Soviet invasion of Hungary. I&apos;m nevertheless not getting a god-that-failed critique vibe here. The novel&apos;s setting involves the destruction of the French Revolution by reactionaries (so there&apos;s that concordance with 1956)--and the protagonist is a proponent of the revolution--he is likely in the revolution&apos;s leftwing, envisioning a radical arborocracy that gr</span>
  <span id="freeText3530622690658731661" style="display:none">Calvino reports, in one of the <i>Hermit in Paris</i> essays, that he wrote this novel in response to leaving the communist party, after the 1956 Soviet invasion of Hungary. I'm nevertheless not getting a god-that-failed critique vibe here. The novel's setting involves the destruction of the French Revolution by reactionaries (so there's that concordance with 1956)--and the protagonist is a proponent of the revolution--he is likely in the revolution's leftwing, envisioning a radical arborocracy that grants rights even to animals and plants. He's accordingly up there with Tom Bombadil, which places him in excellent company. Am not detecting a refutation of his arborescent ideal. That said, "We live in a country where causes are always seen but never effects."<br /><br />The text is almost an inverted companion of Murakami's <i>Wind Up Bird Chronicle</i>, which features a guy who goes into a hole in the ground in order to work out his problem; he does not write a chthonian manifesto--unlike the arboreal baron--identifying the chthonic with unrestrained and unreflective id--very much the metaphor here.<br /><br />Otherwise engaging. An oddity insofar as protagonist is seemingly dominated by an inconsistently available and oscillating Ligeia figure whom he nevertheless abandons to remain in the trees.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3530622690658731661" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


